In short you don&#39;t use **SQLiteStatement**, it&#39;s only intended for/(capable of) returning a single column of a single row as per :-

&gt; Represents a statement that can be executed against a database. The
&gt; statement cannot return multiple rows or columns, but single value (1
&gt; x 1) result sets are supported.
[SQLiteStatement](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/sqlite/SQLiteStatement)

Instead you&#39;d use :-

    SQLiteDatabase db = this.getWritableDatabase();
    Cursor csr = db.query(&quot;tracking&quot;,null /* all columns aka */&quot;,&quot;track_id=?&quot;,new String[]{track_data.getText().toString()},null,null,null);
    while (csr.moveToNext()) {
        // and for each column value you wanted
        my_value = csr.get??????(csr.getColumnIndex(the_column_name_as_a_string)); 
        // e.g. another my_other_value = csr.get??????(csr.getColumnIndex(the_column_name_as_a_string));
    }

- ?????? represents many of the methods e.g. getInt, getLong .........
- see [Cursor](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor)


Or alternately instead of using the convenience method **query**, you could use the **rawQuery** method e.g.

    Cursor csr = db.rawQuery(&quot;Select * from tracking where track_id= ?&quot;,new String[]{track_data.getText().toString()});

