answers.body_markdown:
It&#39;s a mistake to bind DataContext as you&#39;ve done here, because that bound DataContext will be the default source for any other binding on the ComboBox. That gets in the way because you want to be able to bind to properties of the real datacontext, which is the row object, `ImportColumn`. 

We can fix this by using the same RelativeSource you&#39;re using for the DataContext inside your multibinding, which leaves us free to bind ComboBox.SelectedItem to `FileColumnHeader` on the `ImportColumn` for that row. 

```XAML
&lt;DataTemplate&gt;
    &lt;ComboBox 
        VerticalAlignment=&quot;Center&quot; 
        SelectedItem=&quot;{Binding FileColumnHeader}&quot;
        SelectionChanged=&quot;ComboBox_SelectionChanged&quot;
        &gt;
        &lt;ComboBox.ItemsSource&gt;
            &lt;MultiBinding Converter=&quot;{StaticResource listFilterConverter}&quot;&gt;
                &lt;Binding 
                    Path=&quot;DataContext.ListOfWorksheetColumns.UnselectedWorksheetColumns&quot;
                    RelativeSource=&quot;{RelativeSource AncestorType={x:Type ListView}}&quot;
                    /&gt;
                &lt;Binding RelativeSource=&quot;{RelativeSource Self}&quot;/&gt;
            &lt;/MultiBinding&gt;
        &lt;/ComboBox.ItemsSource&gt;
    &lt;/ComboBox&gt;
&lt;/DataTemplate&gt;
```

I&#39;ve learned in comments that the SelectionChanged handler is being used for other stuff that can and arguably should be done in MVVM, but it gets a bit involved. 

For that to work right, `ImportColumn.FileColumnHeader` needs to properly raise PropertyChanged when its value changes. Since you&#39;ve got `ImportColumn` inheriting from something called `BaseViewModel`, I&#39;m going to guess that you may have omitted that detail for the sake of brevity. 

A bit off topic: I&#39;m confident that your `listFilterConverter` should be taking something other than a `ComboBox` as its second parameter. Whatever properties it&#39;s getting from the ComboBox, you should be just binding those properties instead. A converter is much harder to reuse if the consumer needs to wrap its parameters in a `ComboBox`. But that&#39;s not of the essence right now.

